Using AWS Key Management Service (KMS) keys with Amazon S3 buckets in a Cloud Development Kit (CDK) project is a great way to enhance the security of your data. Here's a step-by-step guide on how to do this securely:

### Step 1: Create a KMS Key

First, you need to create a KMS key that will be used to encrypt your S3 bucket. You can do this using the AWS CDK.

```typescript
import * as cdk from 'aws-cdk-lib';
import * as kms from 'aws-cdk-lib/aws-kms';
import * as s3 from 'aws-cdk-lib/aws-s3';

class MyStack extends cdk.Stack {
  constructor(scope: cdk.App, id: string, props?: cdk.StackProps) {
    super(scope, id, props);

    // Create a KMS Key
    const myKmsKey = new kms.Key(this, 'MyKmsKey', {
      description: 'KMS key for S3 bucket encryption',
      enableKeyRotation: true, // Enable automatic key rotation
    });
  }
}
```

### Step 2: Create an S3 Bucket with Server-Side Encryption

Next, create an S3 bucket and configure it to use the KMS key for server-side encryption.

```typescript
class MyStack extends cdk.Stack {
  constructor(scope: cdk.App, id: string, props?: cdk.StackProps) {
    super(scope, id, props);

    // Create a KMS Key
    const myKmsKey = new kms.Key(this, 'MyKmsKey', {
      description: 'KMS key for S3 bucket encryption',
      enableKeyRotation: true,
    });

    // Create an S3 Bucket with server-side encryption using the KMS key
    const myBucket = new s3.Bucket(this, 'MyBucket', {
      encryption: s3.BucketEncryption.KMS,
      encryptionKey: myKmsKey,
